      <h2>What revenge trading actually is</h2>
      <p>
        Revenge trading describes one specific behavioral pattern: placing a new order not because a setup qualifies,
        but because a loss just occurred and the emotional state created by that loss is driving the decision. The entry
        is not based on edge — it is based on the need to recover.
      </p>
      <p>
        The behavioral signature is consistent and measurable. It involves re-entry within an unusually short interval
        after the loss event, often at elevated size, in the same instrument, sometimes in the opposite direction.
        The trader is not following their plan. They are responding to an emotional state.
      </p>

      <h2>Why it is especially destructive in futures trading</h2>
      <p>
        In leveraged futures markets, a single revenge trade can erase a profitable session, breach a prop firm
        drawdown limit, or lock a funded account. The leverage that makes futures attractive also makes the cost of
        a bad decision during psychological deterioration disproportionately high.
      </p>
      <p>
        Most significant single-session drawdowns in retail futures trading do not come from a single bad setup.
        They come from a sequence of revenge trades — each one a response to the previous loss, each one larger or
        less deliberate than the one before it.
      </p>

      <h2>Why willpower and journaling are not sufficient</h2>
      <p>
        The standard advice — slow down, review your journal, remember your plan — is applied after the fact. By the
        time the post-session review identifies a pattern, the loss has already occurred. And in the moment of a loss,
        the neurological response that drives revenge trading specifically impairs the prefrontal cortex — the part
        of the brain that remembers the journal and the plan.
      </p>
      <p>
        A structural solution has to be active at the same time and in the same environment as the failure. Post-session
        insight cannot interrupt a decision that was made mid-session.
      </p>

      <h2>How Meridian detects revenge entry patterns</h2>
      <p>
        Meridian monitors the interval between a loss event and the next order entry, cross-referenced against
        position sizing at that moment. The <strong>Revenge Entry signal</strong> — one of the seven behavioral
        dimensions tracked in the Psychological Stability Index — fires when the re-entry interval and size combination
        falls outside the trader's own historical baseline.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is not a fixed threshold. Meridian compares current behavior against your personal trading history,
        not against a population average. A scalper who normally re-enters within 30 seconds is treated differently
        from a swing trader who normally waits several minutes. The signal fires when your behavior deviates from
        your own norm — not when it deviates from someone else's.
      </p>
      <p>
        When the Revenge Entry signal activates, it contributes to the live PSI score. A single elevated signal
        may move the score into the Caution zone. Multiple signals activating simultaneously — which is common
        during an emotionally driven session — can push PSI toward Critical.
      </p>

      <h2>What Guard can enforce in response</h2>
      <p>
        Meridian Guard translates PSI readings into automatic responses. When PSI crosses a configured threshold —
        or when specific trigger conditions are met directly — Guard can:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Display a visible warning that requires acknowledgment before the next order</li>
        <li>Block new order entry for a configurable duration (mandatory pause)</li>
        <li>Restrict entries until PSI recovers above a defined threshold</li>
        <li>Disconnect from the broker connection entirely at the maximum enforcement level</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        The mandatory pause is the most directly relevant response for revenge trading. It introduces a time-based
        friction between the loss event and any subsequent order. The stress response that drives revenge trading
        is time-limited — cortisol and adrenaline levels drop over minutes. A 10–20 minute enforced pause allows
        partial recovery of deliberate cognitive function before the next entry is possible.
      </p>
      <p>
        Critically, this pause is enforced by the software, not by the trader's decision to apply it. The trigger
        does not ask the trader to exercise judgment at the moment when their judgment is most impaired.
      </p>

      <h2>What Meridian does not do</h2>
